, it was registered as a surname after immigration of its bearers to the US.","Romanian: from the medieval title <i>ban</i> (see   Ban   1), denoting a chief of the territorial unit called <i>banat</i>, + the definite article <i>-u(l)</i>."]},{"name":"Bana","meanings":["Italian: from the feminine form of   Bano  .","Hungarian: from a pet form of the old personal name <i>Bán</i> (see   Ban  ).","Czech (<b>Báňa</b>): nickname from <i>báň</i> ‘arch’, figuratively ‘prison’."]}]},{"name":"Elen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Helen  , now also used outside Wales. It is identical with the Welsh vocabulary word <i>elen</i> ‘nymph’, but this is unlikely to be the origin. It is found in Welsh texts from an early period as an equivalent of <i>Helen</i>, for example as the name of the mother of Constantine, finder of the True Cross."],"variants":[{"name":"Elin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Elen ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elen Banw was born in Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of William Banw. She had at least 2 sons with Hywel ap Jenkin."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1390–1450":"1390–1450","1450":"1450","1390":"1390","Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales","of,Cemias,Pembrokeshire,Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1390–1450":"1390–1450","1450":"1450","1390":"1390","Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales","of,Cemias,Pembrokeshire,Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1390–1450":"1390–1450","1450":"1450","1390":"1390","Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Bedwelty, Monmouthshire, Galles","of,Cemias,Pembrokeshire,Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Elen Banw est née à Pembrokeshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni,